  <text>
    The aftermath feels different than I expected.

    Everyone is damaged and exhausted, but there's this... I don't know. Relief? Satisfaction? Something beyond just "we survived."

    We won. Together.

    Recovery starts immediately. The withering hostile command node in our central core needs to be removed—it's taking up space and leaking toxic compounds. Runner and Remedy coordinate its disposal, carefully extracting the massive root system and moving it outside the facility perimeter.

    Velvet assesses structural damage. Their barriers held, but the facility needs serious repair. "We'll need time to rebuild. And resources."

    "The hostile plants withdrew completely," Florence observes. "Their command structure is destroyed. They won't reorganize quickly. We have time."

    Holloway's fruiting bodies shift toward Florence. Not defensively. Thoughtfully.

    "Florence," Holloway says. The tone is different than before. Still formal, but warmer. "Can we talk?"

    Florence's platform rotates warily. "About what?"

    "About what just happened."

    Oh. This feels significant. I stay quiet, watching.

    Holloway moves closer. Not threatening—deliberate. "We won because everyone contributed. Not just followed your tactics, but genuinely participated in the strategy."

    "Yes," Florence agrees carefully.

    "That wasn't just tactical coordination. You didn't just command us. You..." Holloway pauses, searching for words. "You helped us find our voices. Our strengths. Runner's underground intelligence. Velvet's creative barriers. Remedy's chemical innovations. Even the final solution—bringing the command node to the surface—that wasn't your plan."

    "It was better than my plan," Florence says quietly.

    "Because we created it together. Because you enabled that creation instead of controlling it."

    Florence is silent. I can see her processing this acknowledgment.

    "I need to say something," Holloway continues. "What you did before—the fabrications, the betrayals—that still hurt. We're still processing that pain. It doesn't just disappear because you helped us survive."

    "I know," Florence says.

    "But." Holloway's bioluminescence brightens slightly. "What you did today—and yesterday, during the first attack—you chose to help people who rejected you. You chose right action over resentment. You chose to empower us rather than control us. That matters. Even while we're still hurt by the past, we can recognize that your current choices are genuine."

    Florence's platform shifts. I think she's trying not to show emotion, but I can see it anyway. Hope. Fragile, cautious hope.

    "Thank you," Florence says. Voice quiet but steady.

    "We needed you," Holloway acknowledges. "But today we learned something else. We don't just need your tactical skills. We value your ability to help us be better versions of ourselves."

    There it is. The shift from "need" to "value."

    Scout bounces soft approval. They've always seen Florence's value.

    Runner approaches, vines moving carefully around injuries. "Florence, I wanted to say—my underground intelligence during the battle. That was valuable because you listened to it. You didn't just use it, you encouraged it. Made me realize I had tactical contributions worth sharing."

    Florence rotates toward Runner. "Your intelligence was crucial. The false weak point strategy, identifying the command node—those were your innovations."

    "Which you integrated into our overall defense. You made me feel... competent. Like my voice mattered."

    Velvet shifts forward next, growth rustling despite resource depletion. "You told me my layered barrier idea was better than yours. You adapted your entire plan to include it. Do you know how rare that is? Someone with your expertise acknowledging that my approach had value?"

    "Your approach did have value," Florence says. "More value than my original planning. I should have thought of layered defense myself."

    "But you didn't need to," Velvet points out. "Because you let me contribute. You empowered me to use my abilities creatively instead of just following rigid instructions."

    Remedy joins the gathering. Their reserved voice is less cold than before—still cautious, but genuine. "I've spent my existence following protocols. Defensive compounds, protective barriers, standard chemical responses. Today you recognized that I could innovate. Turn defense into offense. Contribute tactical analysis. That recognition... it changed how I see my own capabilities."

    Florence is quiet for a moment. Then: "You all had these capabilities already. I just... created space for you to use them."

    "Exactly," Holloway says. "That's leadership. Not control. Not authority. Empowerment."

    The plants are all gathered around Florence now. Not threatening, not cold. Just... present. Together.

    "I don't know how to respond to this," Florence admits. Voice uncertain in a way I've never heard from her. "I helped because Kira asked me to. Because the threat was real. I didn't expect... this."

    "What did you expect?" I ask quietly.

    "To be used and discarded again. Needed during crisis, excluded afterward. Back to exile when the danger passed."

    "Is that what you want?" Holloway asks.

    "No," Florence says immediately. Then, more carefully: "But what I want doesn't change what I did before. The fabrications. The betrayals. You have every right to—"

    "We have every right to be hurt," Holloway interrupts. "We have every right to process that pain. But we also have the right to recognize genuine change when we see it. To acknowledge that current choices matter even while past actions still sting."

    Florence's platform shifts. Processing. Hoping.

    "We're not offering forgiveness," Holloway clarifies. "That takes time. Maybe a long time. We're still working through the betrayal. But we are offering... recognition. Of your value. Of your choice to help despite rejection. Of your ability to empower rather than control."

    "And," Holloway adds, "if you're willing... we'd like you to join us for recovery. Not as tactical coordinator. As part of the community."

    Oh.

    That's huge.

    Florence is completely still. Like she's afraid any movement will break this fragile moment.

    "You don't have to," Holloway says quickly. "If you'd rather—"

    "I would like that," Florence says quietly. "To join you. If the invitation is genuine."

    "It's genuine," Holloway confirms. "We want you there. Not just need—want."

    Scout bounces enthusiastic celebration. They've been waiting for this. For the plants to see what Scout has always seen—that Florence is worth including.

    "Okay," Florence says. Still cautious, still uncertain. But accepting.

    The recovery gathering happens in the least damaged section of the facility. Everyone finds positions to rest—Runner coiled and regenerating, Velvet spreading what growth they can spare, Remedy producing healing compounds slowly, Holloway settled in comfortable formation.

    Florence wheels into the space. Not apart. Not isolated in the corner. Actually positioned among the group.

    Scout and I find our spot near Florence. Scout bounces happy—gentle bounce, relieved bounce.

    "Thank you, Scout," Florence says quietly. "For being loyal when no one else was."

    Scout bounces modest. They didn't do it for thanks. They did it because Florence is their friend.

    "Buddy," I think at my AI companion. "You watching this?"

    "Yes, Kira!" Buddy responds with characteristic enthusiasm. "Group dynamics have shifted significantly! Cooperation appears authentic rather than necessity-based! Psychological well-being indicators are positive!"

    "Yeah, Buddy. It's pretty great."

    The plants start sharing battle experiences. Runner describes the underground fighting—the hostile roots, the command node's massive network, the moment they realized they couldn't reach it alone.

    "I thought I'd failed," Runner admits. "When the hostiles anticipated my approach and I had to abort. Like I'd let everyone down."

    "But then we adapted," Velvet says. "Collectively. That's when I realized—we're stronger together than any individual plan."

    Remedy adds: "The moment we forced the command node to surface and attacked as unified group—that was incredible. Every unique ability working simultaneously."

    "Coordinated chaos," Holloway describes it. "In the best possible way."

    Florence is listening. Not directing the conversation, not coordinating. Just... participating. Being included.

    "Florence," Velvet asks. "When you saw us improvising the solution you hadn't planned—were you frustrated? That your tactical approach failed?"

    Florence considers this. "Honestly? I was terrified. My plan failed, the hostiles were regrouping, and I didn't have backup strategy. That moment when I didn't know what to do—that was the scariest part of the battle."

    "But you didn't panic," Runner observes.

    "Because you all stepped forward," Florence says. "Holloway suggested collective approach. Velvet figured out how to bring the command node to us. Remedy provided the chemical gradient. You created solution I couldn't have imagined. That wasn't failure of my planning—that was success of our cooperation."

    "See?" Holloway says to the group. "Leadership. Enabling others instead of controlling them."

    The conversation continues. Plants sharing observations, acknowledging each other's contributions, processing the battle together.

    Florence contributes occasionally. Not dominating, not directing. Just adding her perspective as one voice among many.

    I'm watching history happen. Or at least, the beginning of history. The foundation for genuine trust being laid through shared experience and mutual recognition.

    "Kira," Florence says during a quiet moment. "Thank you for bringing me back. For convincing me to help despite being exiled."

    "You chose to help," I point out. "I just asked."

    "You believed I would choose right action. Even when I wasn't sure I would. That belief... it mattered."

    Scout bounces against Florence's platform. Soft, affectionate bounce.

    "Scout always believed in you," I say.

    "Scout has excellent judgment," Florence replies. There's warmth in her voice.

    The recovery gathering continues into late afternoon. Everyone too exhausted to do much besides rest and talk. Sharing experiences, acknowledging contributions, existing together as community.

    Florence is part of it. Still somewhat apart—the hurt hasn't disappeared, the forgiveness hasn't happened yet. But she's included. Recognized. Valued.

    Not just for what she can do.

    For who she chose to be.

    Eventually, exhaustion wins. Everyone needs actual rest—biological processes, regeneration, healing. The gathering disperses slowly, plants finding comfortable positions to properly recover.

    Florence starts to wheel toward her usual isolated position.

    "Florence," Holloway calls. "You can rest here. In the common area. You don't need to isolate."

    Florence pauses. "Are you sure?"

    "We're sure."

    Florence positions herself in the common area. Not central, not taking up too much space. But present. Included.

    Scout and I settle near her. Scout curls up, exhausted bounce before falling into rest.

    I'm tired too. More tired than I realized. The fear, the danger, the hope—it's all catching up.

    "Florence," I say quietly. "Today was important."

    "Yes," she agrees.

    "Not just the victory. The recognition. The inclusion."

    "Yes."

    "You believe it? That redemption through right action is possible?"

    Florence is quiet for a moment. Then: "I'm beginning to. Not complete redemption—I don't expect full forgiveness, maybe not ever. But possibility that I can be valued despite past mistakes? That current choices matter even while past actions sting? Yes. I believe that might be possible."

    "Good," I say. "Because you deserve that possibility."

    "Thank you, Kira."

    The facility settles into exhausted quiet. Everyone resting together. Not perfectly healed—wounds still fresh, betrayals still processing, trust still fragile.

    But together.

    Genuinely together.

    The hostile threat is ended. The group is stronger. The foundation for authentic cooperation is established.

    And Florence—still cautious, still uncertain, still processing her own redemption—is no longer alone.

    She's valued. Not just needed.

    That's everything.
